# FutFinds — Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
FutFinds is a React Native (Expo) soccer meetup app. Users can create, view, and join local soccer games at fields in their area.

## Tech Stack
- Frontend: React Native with Expo (SDK 51+), using Expo Router for file-based navigation
- Backend/DB: Firebase (Firestore + Auth + Cloud Functions)
- Language: TypeScript (strict mode)
- Forms: react-hook-form
- Maps: react-native-maps with Google Maps
- Date handling: date-fns

## Code Style Rules
- Always use TypeScript. Never use plain .js files for source code.
- Always use functional components with hooks. Never use class components.
- Always define prop types using TypeScript interfaces, not inline types.
- Always use named exports for components, not default exports (exception: Expo Router screens use default exports).
- Use `const` over `let` wherever possible.
- Keep components under 150 lines. Split into smaller components if larger.
- Put all Firebase logic in /firebase/ helper files, never directly in components.
- Put all TypeScript types/interfaces in /types/index.ts.

## Folder Structure
FutFinds/
├── app/                  # Expo Router screens (default exports)
│   ├── (tabs)/
│   │   ├── index.tsx         # List view
│   │   ├── map.tsx           # Map view
│   │   ├── create.tsx        # Create game
│   │   └── account.tsx       # Account/profile
│   ├── game/[id].tsx         # Game detail screen
│   └── auth/                 # Login/signup screens
├── components/           # Reusable UI (named exports)
├── firebase/             # Firebase config and helper functions
├── hooks/                # Custom React hooks (e.g. useGames, useAuth)
├── types/                # TypeScript interfaces
└── assets/

## Firebase Rules
- Always access Firestore through helper functions in /firebase/, never call firebase directly from a screen.
- Always check for authenticated user before any Firestore read/write.
- Use real-time listeners (onSnapshot) for game lists. Use one-time gets (getDoc) for single game detail.

## Firestore Data Models

### Game Document (games/{gameId})
{
  title: string
  type: "scrimmage" | "minigame"
  minigameType: string | null        // e.g. "World Cup", "Wembley", "3hit kill"
  surface: "outdoor" | "indoor" | "futsal"
  fieldName: string
  location: { lat: number, lng: number }
  address: string
  date: string                       // ISO format "YYYY-MM-DD"
  time: string                       // "6:00 PM"
  playersMax: number
  playersJoined: string[]            // array of userIds
  createdBy: string                  // userId
  createdAt: Timestamp
}

### User Document (users/{userId})
{
  displayName: string
  avatar: string | null
  location: string
  gamesCreated: number
  gamesJoined: number
}

## Naming Conventions
- Screens: PascalCase filename, e.g. GameCard.tsx
- Hooks: camelCase prefixed with "use", e.g. useGames.ts
- Firebase helpers: camelCase, e.g. createGame.ts, getGames.ts
- Types: PascalCase interfaces, e.g. Game, AppUser

## AI Behavior Rules
- When generating a new component, always include TypeScript types.
- When writing Firebase functions, always include error handling with try/catch.
- When asked to build a screen, scaffold the full screen with placeholder UI — don't leave empty functions.
- Never install new packages without mentioning it explicitly with the exact install command.
- Always add a comment block at the top of each new file describing what it does.
- If something requires a .env variable (e.g. API keys), flag it clearly with a TODO comment.
- When suggesting changes, only touch the files relevant to the task. Do not refactor unrelated code.
